I’ve seen a lot of these “look poor” videos, but I think many of them are missing a point. You can avoid excess spending and unnecessary luxury goods without “looking poor”. Well-fitting clothes, good grooming, and classic/timeless taste can go a long way. It’s not like we have to decide between Gucci or “look poor”. You can look very classy and upscale on a budget. The reason I say this is because I think some people are going too far in the opposite direction and risk coming across as unkempt or lazy. Even when my family was poor they taught me to look clean and presentable to the world. It had nothing to do with gaudy clothing or brand flexing. There is a middle ground where you don’t have to “look poor” but you also don’t have to spend excessively to achieve a nice look.

I understand the point about luxury brands often being seen as mere signals of disposable income, but I respectfully disagree with that simplistic view.

At its core, luxury should be about taste.

A true luxury brand doesn’t just broadcast wealth—it resonates with personal style and refinement.

It's about craftsmanship, uniqueness, and how well it aligns with the individual’s preferences and lifestyle.

When a luxury brand genuinely matches taste, it transcends its price tag, offering something more meaningful than status: a reflection of who you are.

While some people, particularly the newly wealthy, view luxury brands primarily as symbols of financial status, others recognize them as aligned with their personal ideals. For these individuals, it’s not just about showcasing wealth—it’s about selecting products that resonate with their sense of style, values, and the quality they appreciate. True luxury is about connection to taste and identity, not just economics.
